result.execSummary:
This case is being appealed. If the court makes a decision in a case that a party disagrees with, the party may have the right to seek review by a higher court to determine if the trial court's decision was correct. Appeals are most often made after a trial or final decision in a case, but an appeal can also occur before a final decision.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Minutes filed (ls)

Court in session @ 1:30 p.m. Appearances made. Matter before the Court for final pre-trial, but defendant intends on pleading guilty. Defendant Kyle T Helgeland in court with attorney John Robert Dade.  Diane M. Donohoo appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Attorney Dade informs the Court that the Defendant does not wish to proceed to trial, and would like to enter a guilty plea to both counts, but there is no sentence agreement. Defendant has been engaged in counseling regiments, but has 2 more sessions next week. Attorney Dade requests the Court to allow Defendant to enter pleas next Thursday/Friday as he will be taken into custody once pleas are entered. Defendant does not wish a PSI ordered. Response by ADA Donohoo, who advises the Court of history of the Court. State will be asking for prison and wants a PSI. Response by the Court that he will order short form PSI. Court addresses the defendant regarding his decision to waive his right to a trial. Court gives colloquy regarding his waiver of rights and informs defendant that if he changes his mind regarding trial, matter will be set for court trial. Defendant responds to Court's questions. Court finds the defendant competent to waive his right to trial and informs the parties that jury trial is off the table. State will consent to waiver of jury trial. Court grants the defendant's requests and sets matter over for a plea hearing on May 22, 2015. Clerk to advise DOC that a short form PSI will be ordered and sentencing to be set for June 3, 2015. Court in recess @ 1:45 p.m. Minutes filed.  Plea hearing scheduled for May 22, 2015 at 09:00 am.  Sentencing hearing scheduled for June 3, 2015 at 11:00 am.
